{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/pausing-css-animations-on-hover/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Jack Harner","description":"Jack Harner is a Freelance Web Developer & E-Commerce Consultant based in Denver, Colorado. Shopify, BigCommerce, WordPress Dev & More.","author":"@jackharner","siteUrl":"https://jackharner.com"}},"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>CSS Animations are an easy, lightweight way to add a little motion and excitement to a page. You definitely don't want to overdo it, though. One of the most frustrating things as a user is when you go to click on something, it moves, and you miss.</p>\n<p>Today, I'm going to show you how to pause your CSS animations when someone goes to click on them, <em>without</em> JavaScript.</p>\n<div class=\"table-of-contents\">\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#it-all-starts-with-a-css-animation\">It All Starts With A CSS Animation</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#treat-your-users-like-stormtroopers---avoid-moving-targets\">Treat Your Users Like Stormtroopers - Avoid Moving Targets</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#stop-moving-things-that-dont-need-to-move\">Stop Moving Things That Don't Need To Move</a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<h2 id=\"it-all-starts-with-a-css-animation\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#it-all-starts-with-a-css-animation\" aria-label=\"it all starts with a css animation permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>It All Starts With A CSS Animation</h2>\n<p>We'll start with one of my favorite simple animations, the Pulse. Add the following to your css:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"css\"><pre class=\"language-css\"><code class=\"language-css\"><span class=\"token atrule\"><span class=\"token rule\">@keyframes</span> pulse</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n  <span class=\"token selector\">0%</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token property\">transform</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token function\">scale</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>1<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n  <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n  <span class=\"token selector\">50%</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token property\">transform</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token function\">scale</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>1.1<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n  <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n\n  <span class=\"token selector\">100%</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token property\">transform</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token function\">scale</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>1<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n  <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>and then apply the animation to your element with the <code class=\"language-text\">animation</code> property:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"css\"><pre class=\"language-css\"><code class=\"language-css\"><span class=\"token selector\">.box</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n  <span class=\"token property\">animation</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> pulse 3s infinite\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>All together that looks like: <span class=\"box1\"></span></p>\n<p>I've used that animation many times to emphasize a discount, bring focus to the best deal on a Pricing page, or even just to make a beating heart. As long as your animation is using css and the <code class=\"language-text\">@keyframe</code> property this method will work.</p>\n<p>{{{vert}}}</p>\n<h2 id=\"treat-your-users-like-stormtroopers---avoid-moving-targets\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#treat-your-users-like-stormtroopers---avoid-moving-targets\" aria-label=\"treat your users like stormtroopers   avoid moving targets permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Treat Your Users Like Stormtroopers - Avoid Moving Targets</h2>\n<p>If there are clickable things inside the thing you're animating, you don't want your users to have to click on moving targets. It's so frustrating to click and miss, let alone click, miss, and click on something else. Luckily, there's a really simple way to pause CSS Animations in CSS without JavaScript.</p>\n<p>The key to it all is the <code class=\"language-text\">animation-play-state</code> property. Let's see it in (SCSS) action:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"scss\"><pre class=\"language-scss\"><code class=\"language-scss\"><span class=\"token selector\">.box </span><span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n  <span class=\"token property\">animation</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> pulse 3s infinite<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\n  <span class=\"token selector\"><span class=\"token parent important\">&amp;</span>:hover </span><span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token property\">animation-play-state</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> paused<span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n  <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Which looks like: <span class=\"box2\"></span></p>\n<p>As you can see, it starts and stops the animation when you hover your mouse in and out of it.</p>\n<p>By setting the <code class=\"language-text\">animation-play-state</code> to <code class=\"language-text\">paused</code> on hover, the animation will pause, your click targets will stop moving, and your users will be happy. I had experimented with basically removing the animation on hover but that caused lots of jumps and skips. <code class=\"language-text\">animation-play-state</code> literally just pauses the animation and un-pauses when you stop hovering.</p>\n<h2 id=\"stop-moving-things-that-dont-need-to-move\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#stop-moving-things-that-dont-need-to-move\" aria-label=\"stop moving things that dont need to move permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Stop Moving Things That Don't Need To Move</h2>\n<p>You don't want your users to have to try and click on moving targets. If they miss too many times, they'll get frustrated and no amount of fancy animation will prevent them from leaving for good.</p>\n<p>With great animation power, comes great responsibility. Don't animate things users are supposed to click on, but if you have to, stop moving the thing if it looks like the user is about to click on it.</p>","excerpt":"CSS Animations are an easy, lightweight way to add a little motion and excitement to a page. You definitely don't want to overdo it, though. One of…","wordCount":{"words":381},"frontmatter":{"date":"January 20, 2024","updated":null,"title":"Pausing CSS Animations on Hover","subtitle":"Without Any JavaScript","tags":["CSS","Animation"],"featuredImage":{"absolutePath":"/home/runner/work/jackharner-gatsby/jackharner-gatsby/content/blog/pausing-css-animations-on-hover/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.jpg","childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#080808","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/5267c/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.jpg","srcSet":"/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/7284f/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.jpg 750w,\n/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/29ba9/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.jpg 1080w,\n/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/c8896/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.jpg 1366w,\n/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/5267c/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.jpg 1920w","sizes":"100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/57584/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.webp 750w,\n/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/984df/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.webp 1080w,\n/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/4a276/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.webp 1366w,\n/static/d3bd4a8a2786e50282276c1a3968821d/9c00f/erwan-hesry-IqB5MPcQp6k-unsplash.webp 1920w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"100vw"}]},"width":1,"height":0.6666666666666666}}},"ogImage":null},"fields":{"externalLink":"","externalLinkLabel":"Check It Out »","slug":"/blog/pausing-css-animations-on-h